The paper deals with the problem of parallelizing the single-source shortest path problem, which is a fundamental problem in graph theory and algorithms. The paper proposes a new algorithm called Radius-Stepping, which has the best-known tradeoff between work and depth bounds for SSSP with nearly-linear work. This makes it likely that the paper belongs to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with graph algorithms and properties, which makes it likely to belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) and Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) sub-categories. The paper also uses numerical analysis techniques to analyze the algorithm's performance, which makes it likely to belong to the Numerical Analysis (cs.NA) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with graph theory and optimization, which makes it likely to belong to the Probability (cs.PF) sub-category.
